{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_277c36d9bffe30lq6xpLdFnLNx","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d883c92e6001Q9n4WQL89o7TOM","parts":[{"id":"prt_d883ca6ca0015htSuiSE85gAfK","messageID":"msg_d883c92e6001Q9n4WQL89o7TOM","sessionID":"ses_277c36d9bffe30lq6xpLdFnLNx","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_2a6fff03327a47b4aa9a96b1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: [![Support Ukraine](https://img.shields.io/badge/Support-Ukraine-FFD500?style=flat&labelColor=005BBB)](https://opensource.fb.com/support-ukraine) [![CircleCI](https://circleci.com/gh/facebookresearch/nevergrad/tree/main.svg?style=svg)](https://circleci.com/gh/facebookresearch/nevergrad/tree/main)\n2: \n3: # Nevergrad - A gradient-free optimization platform\n4: \n5: ![Nevergrad](docs/resources/Nevergrad-LogoMark.png)\n6: \n7: \n8: `nevergrad` is a Python 3.8+ library. It can be installed with:\n9: \n10: ```\n11: pip install nevergrad\n12: ```\n13: \n14: More installation options, including windows installation, and complete instructions are available in the \"Getting started\" section of the [**documentation**](https://facebookresearch.github.io/nevergrad/).\n15: \n16: You can join Nevergrad users Facebook group [here](https://www.facebook.com/groups/nevergradusers/).\n17: \n18: Minimizing a function using an optimizer (here `NGOpt`) is straightforward:\n19: \n20: ```python\n21: import nevergrad as ng\n22: \n23: def square(x):\n24:     return sum((x - .5)**2)\n25: \n26: optimizer = ng.optimizers.NGOpt(parametrization=2, budget=100)\n27: recommendation = optimizer.minimize(square)\n28: print(recommendation.value)  # recommended value\n29: >>> [0.49971112 0.5002944]\n30: ```\n31: \n32: `nevergrad` can also support bounded continuous variables as well as discrete variables, and mixture of those.\n33: To do this, one can specify the input space:\n34: \n35: ```python\n36: import nevergrad as ng\n37: \n38: def fake_training(learning_rate: float, batch_size: int, architecture: str) -> float:\n39:     # optimal for learning_rate=0.2, batch_size=4, architecture=\"conv\"\n40:     return (learning_rate - 0.2)**2 + (batch_size - 4)**2 + (0 if architecture == \"conv\" else 10)\n41: \n42: # Instrumentation class is used for functions with multiple inputs\n43: # (positional and/or keywords)\n44: parametrization = ng.p.Instrumentation(\n45:     # a log-distributed scalar between 0.001 and 1.0\n46:     learning_rate=ng.p.Log(lower=0.001, upper=1.0),\n47:     # an integer from 1 to 12\n48:     batch_size=ng.p.Scalar(lower=1, upper=12).set_integer_casting(),\n49:     # either \"conv\" or \"fc\"\n50:     architecture=ng.p.Choice([\"conv\", \"fc\"])\n51: )\n52: \n53: optimizer = ng.optimizers.NGOpt(parametrization=parametrization, budget=100)\n54: recommendation = optimizer.minimize(fake_training)\n55: \n56: # show the recommended keyword arguments of the function\n57: print(recommendation.kwargs)\n58: >>> {'learning_rate': 0.1998, 'batch_size': 4, 'architecture': 'conv'}\n59: ```\n60: \n61: Learn more on parametrization in the [**documentation**](https://facebookresearch.github.io/nevergrad/)!\n62: \n63: ![Example of optimization](docs/resources/TwoPointsDE.gif)\n64: \n65: *Convergence of a population of points to the minima with two-points DE.*\n66: \n67: \n68: ## Documentation\n69: \n70: Check out our [**documentation**](https://facebookresearch.github.io/nevergrad/)! It's still a work in progress, so don't hesitate to submit issues and/or pull requests (PRs) to update it and make it clearer!\n71: The last version of our [**data**](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1p8d1bMCDlvWrDIMXP7fT9pJa1cgjH3NM/view?usp=sharing) and the last version of our [**PDF report**](https://tinyurl.com/dagstuhloid). \n72: \n73: ## Citing\n74: \n75: ```bibtex\n76: @misc{nevergrad,\n77:     author = {J. Rapin and O. Teytaud},\n78:     title = {{Nevergrad - A gradient-free optimization platform}},\n79:     year = {2018},\n80:     publisher = {GitHub},\n81:     journal = {GitHub repository},\n82:     howpublished = {\\url{https://GitHub.com/FacebookResearch/Nevergrad}},\n83: }\n84: ```\n85: \n86: ## License\n87: \n88: `nevergrad` is released under the MIT license. See [LICENSE](LICENSE) for additional details about it.\n89: See also our [Terms of Use](https://opensource.facebook.com/legal/terms) and [Privacy Policy](https://opensource.facebook.com/legal/privacy).\n\n(End of file - total 89 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"[![Support Ukraine](https://img.shields.io/badge/Support-Ukraine-FFD500?style=flat&labelColor=005BBB)](https://opensource.fb.com/support-ukraine) [![CircleCI](https://circleci.com/gh/facebookresearch/nevergrad/tree/main.svg?style=svg)](https://circleci.com/gh/facebookresearch/nevergrad/tree/main)\n\n# Nevergrad - A gradient-free optimization platform\n\n![Nevergrad](docs/resources/Nevergrad-LogoMark.png)\n\n\n`nevergrad` is a Python 3.8+ library. It can be installed with:\n\n```\npip install nevergrad\n```\n\nMore installation options, including windows installation, and complete instructions are available in the \"Getting started\" section of the [**documentation**](https://facebookresearch.github.io/nevergrad/).\n\nYou can join Nevergrad users Facebook group [here](https://www.facebook.com/groups/nevergradusers/).\n\nMinimizing a function using an optimizer (here `NGOpt`) is straightforward:\n\n```python","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.md","time":{"start":1776107169903,"end":1776107169914}}}]}
